<div id="review_153386312" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/153386312" />
    <a title="Catie" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/1886642-catie"><img alt="Catie" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1385169623p2/1886642.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/153386312?book_show_action=true">Mar 10, 2011</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Catie" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Catie" href="/user/show/1886642-catie">Catie</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/1886642-catie?shelf=read-in-2011">read-in-2011</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/1886642-catie?shelf=fantasy">fantasy</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/1886642-catie?shelf=series">series</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/1886642-catie?shelf=ya">ya</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/1886642-catie?shelf=audio">audio</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer153386312" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer7604181525703042011">If you, like me, have always wished that Tamora Pierce and Anne McCaffrey would finally admit their deep, abiding love for one another; make it official with a short ceremony in Massachusetts; then decide to start a family by adopting a fierce Asian baby, then I think you will fall in love with this book.<br/><br/>This is the powerful story of Eon, a young candidate for apprentice Dragoneye. If he is selected, he will commune and share power with one of the twelve Dragons, which are energy based creatures</span>
  <span id="freeText7604181525703042011" style="display:none">If you, like me, have always wished that Tamora Pierce and Anne McCaffrey would finally admit their deep, abiding love for one another; make it official with a short ceremony in Massachusetts; then decide to start a family by adopting a fierce Asian baby, then I think you will fall in love with this book.<br /><br />This is the powerful story of Eon, a young candidate for apprentice Dragoneye. If he is selected, he will commune and share power with one of the twelve Dragons, which are energy based creatures that represent each animal in the Chinese zodiac. Eon, a disfigured, weak candidate is given the lowest odds of selection and viewed as useless by his teachers. But what they don’t know is that Eon and his master are carrying out an elaborate deception: Eon is really Eona, a girl with the rare ability to see all twelve dragons.<br /><br />The writing is intense and action-packed. I was terribly hooked to this one. Despite my dislike of the audiobook narrator, this is one of the rare books that I listened to and read in tandem just so I didn’t have to put it down. I think that most people will figure out the “endgame” of Eon’s power acquisition early on, as it is heavily alluded to. Yes, I did get frustrated a bit in the middle as poor Eon struggles and can’t seem to cotton on to what’s really happening. Especially when <a class="jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction">(view spoiler)</a><span class="spoilerContainer" style="display: none">[she’s like, “Huh. Whenever I use this powder, my dragon gets hazy and the mystical accessory that’s linked to her lets go of me. Weird. You know what I think will fix that for sure? Taking more powder!! “ <a class="jsHideSpoiler spoilerAction">(hide spoiler)</a>]</span> However, none of that frustration kept me from buying into the story. The Dragoneye culture denies women so harshly; it’s believable that Eon would try to deny her feminine side as well. Happily, all that frustration and hopelessness only funds an extremely big pay-off later. I can’t even say how incredibly awesome the ending is. It is so awesome that I wish I had read it in the middle of a massive canyon of some sort, so that I could drop to my knees, raise my fists to the sky, and shout, “EONA!!!” And then hear it echoing all around me. That’s how awesome it is.<br /><br />This book explores the balance and interchange of the masculine and feminine; the competition between compassion and ruthlessness. This is explored through philosophical discussions and dilemmas, but also through characters. Eon struggles to accept her dual nature, but there are numerous other characters in the story that represent this struggle as well. I utterly adore Lady Dela. To me, she is the strongest representation of balance between masculine and feminine and the strength that arises from that. When she scolds Eon for deceiving everyone, it is so satisfying (yet another balm for my earlier frustrations).<br /><br />One of the more fulfilling parts of this book is that, although there is a slight “cliffhanger” at the end, there is a good amount of resolution. I also noticed this fabulous sentence on the last page: “The struggle for the Empire of the Celestial Dragons will conclude in Eona The Last Dragoneye.” That means there’s only a matter of days before I can have closure!! Woo!<br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="7604181525703042011" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


