  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_1891556798" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1891556798" />
    <a title="Veronique" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/12371602-veronique"><img alt="Veronique" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1590509341p2/12371602.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1891556798?book_show_action=true">Jan 26, 2017</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Veronique" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Veronique" href="/user/show/12371602-veronique">Veronique</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Kindle Edition " href="/book/show/12107847-eon">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/12371602-veronique?shelf=r2017">r2017</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/12371602-veronique?shelf=stars-4-0">stars-4-0</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1891556798" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer2131161884071986164"><i>“You are wrong when you say there is no power in being a woman. When I think of my mother and the women in my tribe, and the hidden women in the harem, I know there are many types of power in this world...I found power in accepting the truth of who I am. It may not be a truth that others can accept, but I cannot live any other way. How would it be to live a lie every minute of your life? I don&apos;t think I could do it.” </i><br/><br/>Having really enjoyed Goodman’s <a href='https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/27074515.The_Dark_Days_Club__Lady_Helen___1_' title='The Dark Days Club (Lady Helen, #1) by Alison Goodman' rel='nofollow noopener'>The Dark Days Club</a>, I was curious to try anothe</span>
  <span id="freeText2131161884071986164" style="display:none"><i>“You are wrong when you say there is no power in being a woman. When I think of my mother and the women in my tribe, and the hidden women in the harem, I know there are many types of power in this world...I found power in accepting the truth of who I am. It may not be a truth that others can accept, but I cannot live any other way. How would it be to live a lie every minute of your life? I don't think I could do it.” </i><br /><br />Having really enjoyed Goodman’s <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/27074515.The_Dark_Days_Club__Lady_Helen___1_" title="The Dark Days Club (Lady Helen, #1) by Alison Goodman" rel="nofollow noopener">The Dark Days Club</a>, I was curious to try another of her books. The first thing that hits you in this novel is the world building. The author paints an amazing and complex setting based on Chinese/Japanese culture, combined with a magic system grounded in martial arts and astrology. The result is indeed fascinating and we follow Eon, a sixteen-year old girl masquerading as a boy, with the hope of becoming a Dragoneye apprentice, role forbidden to women. <br /><br />To say that there is much at stake is an understatement, the balance between life and death ever so thin. This is a violent patriarchal world and Goodman doesn’t hide this fact. On the contrary! Be aware therefore that this book won’t suit every reader out there, especially since <i>Eon</i> has been marketed as YA.<br /><br />Coming back to the characters, Eon/Eona is an engaging heroine. The trope of disguising oneself is not a new one but the author weaves this throughout the plot on all levels. Not only this, but she adds a very diverse cast, two being particularly fascinating protagonists, one a transgender, the other a eunuch. <br /><br />I’m left wanting to find out a lot more about this world, its inhabitants, and the history of the Mirror Dragon. Yes, I shall be reading the second book in this duology.<br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="2131161884071986164" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


